<p>Qantas said on Sunday that personal data for up to 5.7 million customers stolen earlier this year has been posted online, and it is working with cybersecurity experts and Australian authorities to assess the exposure [japantoday.com#1][ndtv.com#1]. The airline said the information was taken in a July cyberattack on its third‑party provider Salesforce, with leaked records including names, emails and Frequent Flyer details, and for a smaller number, addresses, dates of birth, phone numbers, gender and meal preferences [michaelwest.com.au#1][firstpost.com#1]. Qantas and reports emphasized that no credit card or passport details, and no passwords, PINs or Frequent Flyer logins were compromised [michaelwest.com.au#1][firstpost.com#1]. The hackers, identified as Scattered LAPSUS$ Hunters, claimd</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/qi9ICVpHY6kLhMU6fqQJqULqaSofZZfr0y4JtQ1Y1xdGdTY6zoey2PKLoyoo_aOZdHmxBR907sZomeMbai1naR0bC4y3l-fBvwkNlP1EHfgYXfzN5AYrVxEIy-08syCeyF0q0J0aQdqmopZWN09IqpZYAFKIqjytMUQn5m-VmKKcqUYKmQ' alt='Cybersecurity illustration highlighting data protection and online threats.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Scope of leak: Qantas says data for up to 5.7 million customers was posted online following theft earlier this year [japantoday.com#1][ndtv.com#1].</li><li>Data included: Leaked records included names, emails and Frequent Flyer details, and for fewer customers, addresses, dates of birth, phone numbers, gender and meal preferences [michaelwest.com.au#1].</li><li>Sensitive data spared: No credit card or passport details were exposed, and no passwords, PINs or Frequent Flyer logins were compromised, according to Qantas [michaelwest.com.au#1][firstpost.com#1].</li><li>Attack source: The breach stemmed from a July cyberattack on Qantas’s third‑party platform provider Salesforce; the data was later posted to the dark web [michaelwest.com.au#1][firstpost.com#1].</li><li>Company response: Qantas is investigating with cybersecurity experts and Australian authorities, and obtained an NSW Supreme Court injunction to restrict use of the stolen data [ndtv.com#1][michaelwest.com.au#1].</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Qantas: The airline says it is investigating the release with specialist cybersecurity experts and Australian authorities to determine the extent of exposure. (<a href='https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/australian-airline-qantas-says-stolen-customer-data-posted-online-after-cyberattack-9440346#publisher=newsstand'>NDTV</a>)</li><li>Salesforce: The hackers threatened to release data unless a ransom was paid; Salesforce refused to pay the undisclosed ransom. (<a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/its-all-over-the-place-qantas-customer-data-leaked/'>Michael West Media</a>)</li><li>Troy Hunt (Have I Been Pwned): A security researcher verified his own Qantas data was in the leak, including family names and a Frequent Flyer balance, indicating authenticity. (<a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/its-all-over-the-place-qantas-customer-data-leaked/'>Michael West Media</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://japantoday.com/category/world/australian-airline-qantas-says-millions-of-customers%27-data-leaked-online'>Australian airline Qantas says millions of customers&#x27; data leaked online</a> - japantoday.com</li><li><a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/its-all-over-the-place-qantas-customer-data-leaked/'>‘It’s all over the place’: Qantas customer data leaked</a> - michaelwest.com.au</li><li><a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/hack-hits-australian-airline-qantas-leaks-data-of-5-7-million-customers-online-13941381.html'>Hack hits Australian airline Qantas, leaks data of 5.7 million customers online</a> - firstpost.com</li><li><a href='https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/australian-airline-qantas-says-stolen-customer-data-posted-online-after-cyberattack-9440346#publisher=newsstand'>Australian Airline Says Stolen Customer Data Posted Online After Cyberattack</a> - ndtv.com</li></ul>